    "content": "<p>Consider the following statements:</p>\n<p>Statement (I): In a LPP, the objective function is always linear.</p>\n<p>Statement (II): Ina LPP, the linear inequalities on variables are called constraints. Which of the following is correct?</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": " Statement (I) is true, Statement (II) is true\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": " Statement (I) is true, Statement (II) is false\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": " Both Statements (I) and (II) are false\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": " Statement (I) is false, Statement (II) is true"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Option A. Both statements are true.</p>\n<p>Reasoning:</p>\n\n<p><p>By definition, a Linear Programming Problem (LPP) has a linear objective function, for example  </p>\n<p>$$\\max z = c_1x_1 + c_2x_2 + \\dots + c_nx_n.$$</p></p>\n<p><p>The restrictions on the variables take the form of linear inequalities (or equalities), such as  </p>\n<p>$$a_{i1}x_1 + a_{i2}x_2 + \\dots + a_{in}x_n \\;\\le\\; b_i,$$  </p>\n<p>and these are called constraints.</p></p>\n",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2025,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2025",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
